style="font-size: 22px;">Figure 1: Industrial Capitalism</font></h1><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Here we depict the primordial relationship between industrial production and capital. There are four dimensions: 1. Generation of new capital from the mining profits; 2. Extraction of private wealth for consumption. 3. Note that the relationship between the Steam Pumps and Coal Mining Company is inside a Production Network.</span></p>" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry height="130" width="803" x="17" y="630" as="geometry" /> 0px;"><font style="font-size: 22px;">Figure 2: Industrial Capital - Positive Feedback</font></h1><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This is just a simplified version of Fig. 1 to highlight the positive feedback loop of capital in the relationship between the primary and secondary industry sectors. If you wanted to replace capitalism with another market driven form of trade then you would need to replicate this feedback loop to compete. Fig 7. of my Production Theory shows you where to do that by presenting the functional connection that has always existed between different supply chains.</span></p>" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry height="150" width="722" x="38" y="420" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> </root> </mxGraphModel> </diagram> </mxfile>

p.span: This is just a simplified version of Fig. 1 to highlight the positive feedback loop of capital in the relationship between the primary and secondary industry sectors. If you wanted to replace capitalism with another market driven form of trade then you would need to replicate this feedback loop to compete. Fig 7. of my Production Theory shows you where to do that by presenting the functional connection that has always existed between different supply chains.
